Day 8 — Git Basics, Commits & Repository Setup

What I Learned

Git is a version control system used to track changes and collaborate.

Installed Git and configured user identity using user.name and user.email.

Created a new local repository using git init.

Files must be added to staging area before committing using git add.

git commit creates a snapshot of tracked changes.

Connected local repo to GitHub using git remote add origin.

GitHub no longer supports password authentication — we must use Personal Access Token.

git push uploads commits to GitHub.

credential.helper store saves token locally to avoid retyping.


Commands / Code

# Check git version
git --version

# Configure identity for commits
git config --global user.name "Godwin Gerald"
git config --global user.email "renaldamalogodwin2007@gmail.com"

git config --global credential.helper store   # Save token for future pushes

# Create project and initialize Git
mkdir GitPractice
cd GitPractice
git init

# Create file & track changes
echo "Hello Git" > file.txt
git status
git add file.txt

# Commit changes
git commit -m "Initial commit"

# Connect to GitHub repository
git remote add origin https://github.com/godwin2707/GitPractice.git

# Rename branch to main (if needed)
git branch -M main

# Push code to GitHub (use PAT as password)
git push -u origin main

# Check remote URL
git remote -v

Notes

Git works in three stages: Working Directory → Staging → Commit.

git add . stages all files; git commit saves snapshot history.

Never use GitHub password for pushing — use Personal Access Token (PAT).

After configuring credential.helper store, Git remembers the token.

git status is used frequently to track uncommitted changes.

Git is essential for DevOps pipelines, CI/CD builds, collaboration, and code rollback.

